{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = Antarctic Conquest | title_orig = | translator = | image = Antarctic Conquest.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[Finn Ronne]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Exploration]] | publisher = [[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] | release_date = 1949 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Antarctic Conquest: the Story of the Ronne Expedition 1946-1948''''' is a 1949 [[science book]] by [[Norwegian-American]] [[Antarctica|Antarctic]] explorer [[Finn Ronne]] and [[science fiction]] writer [[L. Sprague de Camp]], published in hardcover by [[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]. The role of de Camp, who was commissioned as a [[ghost writer]] to recast Ronne's manuscript into publishable form, is uncredited. Ronne's working title was reportedly "Conquering the Antarctic".<ref>{{cite book | last=Laughlin | first=Charlotte | author2=Daniel J. H. Levack | title=De Camp: An L. Sprague de Camp Bibliography | location=San Francisco | publisher=Underwood/Miller | year=1983 | page=26}}</ref>
==Summary== The book relates the story of the [[Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition]], which researched the area surrounding the head of the [[Weddell Sea]] in Antarctica from 1947-1948.
==Relationship to other works== De Camp's work with Ronne is reflected in two of his contemporary ''[[Viagens Interplanetarias]]'' science fiction stories set on the fictional planet Krishna. One, the short story "[[Calories (story)|Calories]]," adopts an Antarctic setting not utilized in any of the series's other stories; in the other, the novel ''[[The Hand of Zei]]'', the protagonist adopts the alias of an inhabitant of the planet's Antarctic and is, like de Camp, employed as a ghostwriter for his explorer boss.
