{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image=Pisces V- noaa nur07527.jpg | Ship caption= }}
{{Infobox ship characteristics}} |- | Name: | Pisces V |- | Country: | USA |- | | {{USN flag|1972}} |- | Length: | 20&nbsp;ft |- | Width: | 10&nbsp;ft 6in |- | Height: | 11&nbsp;ft |- | Weight: | 13 tons |- | Crew: | 1 Pilot 2 Observers |- | Life support: | 140 hours for 3 people |- | Maximum operating depth: | 6,280&nbsp;ft(~2000m) |- | Power: | 2 lead-acid battery systems |- | Propulsion: | 2 side mounted reversible thrusters tiltable through 90 degrees |- | Speed: | 3 Kts |- | Dive duration: | 7–9 hours |- | Materials: | Personnel sphere, Trim sphere, and Aft sphere: HY 100 steel |- | Frame: | Welded, oil-filled, pressure compensated tubular steel |- | Viewports: | 3 forward-looking acrylic windows, 6" interior-14" dia exterior |- |}
'''''Pisces V''''' is a type of manned [[submersible]] ocean exploration device, powered by battery, and capable of operating to depths of {{convert|2000|m|ft}}, a depth that is optimum for use in the sea waters around the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. It is used by scientists to explore the deep sea around the underwater banks in the main Hawaiian Islands, as well as the underwater features and [[seamount]]s in the Northwestern Hawaiian Islands, specifically around [[Loihi Seamount]].<ref name="noas">{{cite web |url=http://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/technology/subs/pisces/pisces.html |title=NOAA Ocean Explorer: Pisces IV and V |publisher=oceanexplorer.noaa.gov |accessdate=2009-05-08 |last=Shackelford |first=Rachel }} </ref>
In 1973, ''Pisces V'' took part in the [[rescue of Roger Mallinson and Roger Chapman]], who were trapped on the seabed in ''Pisces V''{{'}}s sister submersible ''[[Pisces III]]''.<ref name="Chapman">{{cite book|last=Chapman|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger R. Chapman|title=No Time On Our Side|publisher=[[W. W. Norton & Company]]|location=[[New York City|New York]]|year=1975|isbn=0-393-03186-1|lccn=75-19154|pages=98–111, 127–129}}</ref> In August 2002, ''Pisces V'' and her sister ''Pisces IV'' discovered a [[World War II]] [[Ko-hyoteki class submarine|Japanese midget submarine]] outside of [[Pearl Harbor]] which had been sunk by the [[destroyer]] {{USS|Ward|DD-139|6}} in the [[first American shots fired in World War II]]. In 2011, marine scientists from [[Hawaii Undersea Research Laboratory|HURL]] celebrated the 1,000 dives of ''Pisces V'' and ''Pisces IV''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Students nationwide virtually participate in Hawaii Undersea Research Laboratory’s 1,000th Pisces submersible dive|url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2011/20110405_hurl.html|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2011-04-10|date=2011-04-05}}</ref>
==Uses== [[File:Cauldron sponge.jpg|thumb|''Pisces V''’s manipulator arm taking a sample of the "cauldron sponge".]]
The advantage of having two is that it allows preparation for an emergency. While one of the submersibles is conducting its dive, the other remains at readiness should there be an emergency, needing to be boarded on ship and hurried to the site of the problem. Such an emergency could include the submersible becoming tangled in fishing nets or entrapped in rocks or debris on the ocean floor. In such cases, the second heads to the rescue. There are also research experiments where it is advantageous to use the two vessels together.<ref name="noas"/>
In August 2002, ''Pisces V'' and her sister vessel ''Pisces IV'' discovered a [[Ko-hyoteki class submarine|Japanese midget submarine]]; sunk on December 7, 1941 by the [[destroyer]] {{USS|Ward|DD-139|6}} in the [[first American shots fired in World War II]], the submarine was hit by a [[4"/50 caliber gun|4"/50&nbsp;caliber gun]] shot and [[depth charge]]d shortly before the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] began. The submarine was found in {{convert|400|m|ft}} of water about {{convert|5|mi}} off the mouth of [[Pearl Harbor]].<ref name="soest"> {{cite web |url=http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/HURL/midget.html |title=Japanese Midget Submarine |publisher=www.soest.hawaii.edu |accessdate=2009-09-13 |first=John C. |last=Wiltshire }} </ref><ref>{{cite DANFS | title = Ward | url = http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/w3/ward.htm | accessdate = 2008-05-13 }}</ref> This was the culmination of a 61-year search for the vessel and has been called "the most significant modern marine archeological find ever in the Pacific, second only to the finding of ''Titanic'' in the Atlantic".<ref name="soest"/> In 2003, ''Pisces V'' visited the Japanese midget submarine it had found in Pearl Harbor the year before. The [[U.S. State Department]] worked in conjunction with the [[Japanese Foreign Ministry]] to determine Japanese wishes regarding the fate of the midget submarine.<ref> {{cite web |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2003/08/24/news/story6.html |title=Exploring the Deep: UH researchers who found a mini-sub will dive around the northwest islands |publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |accessdate=2009-05-08 |date=August 24, 2003 |last=Altoon |first=Helen }} </ref> The submersibles are used by HURL as teaching devices. In 2008, two members of the Tampa Bay Chapter of SCUBAnauts were invited to team with HURL and to visit the historic wreck of the Japanese submarine. One SCUBAnaut said as he stepped on ''Pisces V'' that "it looked and felt as if I were in a space shuttle preparing for lift-off".<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.oar.noaa.gov/spotlite/2008/spot_deepclimb.html |title=NOAA Supports Young Explorers in Seafloor to Mountaintop to Outer Space Challenge |publisher=www.oar.noaa.gov |accessdate=2009-05-08 |first1= Christine |last1= Patrick |first2=Fred |last2= Gorell }} </ref> A mock-up of the control panel of ''Pisces V'' can be visited by the public at the [[Mokupapapa Discovery Center|Mokupāpapa Discovery Center]] in [[Hilo, Hawaii]].<ref name="center">{{cite web| url=http://www.hawaiireef.noaa.gov/education/center.html |title=Mokupāpapa: Discovery Center |publisher=Northwestern Hawaiian Islands Coral Reef Ecosystem Reserve |accessdate=2009-09-13 }}</ref>
On March 5, 2009, scientists discovered seven new species of [[bamboo coral]], six of which may be of a new genus, an extraordinary finding in a genus so broad. They were able to find these specimens through the use of ''Pisces V'' which allowed them to reach depths beyond those attained by scuba divers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insciences.org/article.php?article_id=3008 |title=New Deep-Sea Coral Discovered on NOAA-Supported Mission - insciences |publisher=insciences.org |accessdate=2009-05-08 |first1= Christine |last1= Patrick |first2=Keeley |last2=Belva }}</ref><ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/03/090305121657.htm |title=Seven New Species Of Deep-sea Coral Discovered |publisher=www.sciencedaily.com |date=March 6, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-08 }} </ref> They also discovered a giant sponge approximately three feet tall and three feet wide that scientists named the "cauldron sponge".<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2009/20090305_coral.html |title=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration - New Deep-Sea Coral Discovered on NOAA-Supported Mission |publisher=www.noaanews.noaa.gov |date=March 5, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-11}}</ref>
